I personally am looking forward to it.  <p><a href=http://www.hneguild.com/profile.asp?name=Garbhad><img src="http://value.net/~cblack/eqpics/Garbsig.jpg"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tain>Tain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:orange;'>Tavern Resident</span></span><br>  Posts: 1414<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(2/10/03 11:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntaverncommonsroom.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5017.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: uh...</span><hr size=1> Sony/VI have always understimated the powergaming abilities of it's players.  Every expansion to EQ (PoP excluced?  Dunno.) has left the highest end stuff unfinished because they thought they'd have plenty of time to patch it in later.  Players always got there first. <br>
<br>
There'll never be an EQ &quot;killer&quot; because there'll never be a market like EQ had when it came out.  It was a big thing, and the only big thing, with zero competition.  By the time competition started appearing people were too invested with their EQ characters.  That's still the case, and it's why most people still play EQ.  Not because it's the most fun, but because they're not able to let go and admit to themselves that they don't have anything tangible to show for the hundreds of hours they've spent playing.  <br>
<br>
Now that's not every single player of course, there are people playing simply because they still enjoy playing, for one reason or another.  But it's going to take more than just &quot;the best&quot; game out there to get EQ type subscriber numbers.  The market simply won't support that anymore.  There's a limited number of people who want to play EQ type games, and the number of options out there for them keep growing.  The ironic thing is the games that had the best chance to get a big piece of EQ's playerbase early on blew it by trying to jump into the market too soon, with too many problems.  Asheron's Call is the best example, if they had waited another six months to release and added more content, it would have had a much better chance of succeeding than when it was rushed out the door.  Anarchy Online had a good shot because it was something different, but launched with far too many bugs and scared people off.  Once you do that it doesn't matter if you fix things later, most people won't come back. <br>
<br>
In order to pull players companies are going to have to put out something new.  Really new.  Star Wars will get people.  Shadowbane, Worlds of Warcarft, and anything else in a similar genre, will garner small support for being quality games, but never mass market appeal.  The &quot;casual&quot; gamer will see swords, spells, monsters, and not be enticed to go away from what they've already spent three years in EQ doing. <p>-Tain<BR>
