<br>
People have been getting &quot;bored&quot; of EQ since before Kunark, and every few months since then.  They're still playing.  <br>
<br>
I never said that people wouldn't play other games.  I said that no game in the forseeable future would garner the same subscription levels as EverQuest.  What remains to be seen for sure is how successfull a game can be long term without having 100,000+ subscribers.  DAoC seems to be doing ok for now, at least it hasn't shut down yet.  Anarchy Online did it's best to scare away it's entire userbase early on, but they are still out there.  But the days of EVERYONE playing a single game are gone, instead you'll have DAOC with 50k subscribers, AO with 20k, WoW with 40k, City of Heroes with 20k, A Tale in the Desert with 10k, Star Wars Galaxies, etc. etc. etc.   Completely fictional numbers pulled out of thin air for demonstration purposes. <br>
<br>
People will not simply quit EQ en masse and play something else.  People leave, try something else, realize it's the same process of levelling, killing, crafting, etc. and figure why go through all of that again when you've already did it once and have something to show for it.  A lot go back to EQ.  That won't last forever, but it'll hold for a while longer.  The longer it goes the more options there will be for other games, the more saturated the market will be.  There still are a limited subset of playes who are willing to put in the time and money required to succed in a MMORPG, and the more games there are the more those people will be spread out.  Keep in mind there are still people who play UO, even with so many other games out there.  A lot of EQ people still have their UO accounts active, just as a lot of people who play other games still have their EQ accounts, just in case.  <br>
 <p>-Tain<BR>
